meta.type_name: Software errors and their fixes - tests asymmetric problem→solution flow

patterns.example: AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'get' → Check if variable was initialized → Add null check before method call
patterns.why_asymmetric: Solution adds actionable value to error; error doesn't help someone already implementing the solution

patterns.example: Race condition in thread pool ↔ Use thread-safe queue with locks
patterns.why_symmetric: Understanding cause helps choose prevention; prevention validates cause hypothesis

patterns.description: Same technology/framework mentioned but wrong error type or unrelated feature
examples: Django authentication error paired with Django ORM optimization tip
React useState error paired with React routing configuration
patterns.why_negative: Shares keywords but solution doesn't address the actual problem type

meta.type_name: Household problems and fixes - tests practical troubleshooting across physical systems

patterns.example: Water pools under sink → Check P-trap seal → Replace worn rubber gasket
patterns.why_asymmetric: Repair instruction adds value to symptom; symptom doesn't help someone already repairing

patterns.example: Clean HVAC filter monthly ↔ Prevents compressor overheating
patterns.why_symmetric: Maintenance makes sense given failure; failure justifies maintenance effort

patterns.description: Same room/appliance but completely different system
examples: Leaky faucet paired with electrical outlet not working
Refrigerator ice maker issue paired with refrigerator light bulb replacement
patterns.why_negative: Same appliance keywords but functionally independent systems

meta.type_name: Symptoms and their clinical responses - tests diagnostic reasoning flows

patterns.example: Persistent dry cough over 3 weeks → Check for postnasal drip and GERD → Elevate bed head, avoid late meals
patterns.why_asymmetric: Intervention addresses symptom; symptom doesn't guide someone already treating

patterns.example: Family history of colon cancer ↔ Colonoscopy starting age 40
patterns.why_symmetric: Risk factor justifies screening; screening targets risk factor

patterns.description: Same body system but unrelated conditions
examples: Chest pain from heartburn paired with advice for asthma management
Knee arthritis paired with ankle sprain treatment
patterns.why_negative: Same anatomical area but different pathophysiology

patterns.example: Laptop won't charge → Check LED indicator and try different outlet → Replace AC adapter
patterns.why_asymmetric: Fix procedure resolves malfunction; malfunction doesn't help someone already fixing

patterns.example: Smart TV doesn't support VPN apps ↔ Configure VPN on router level
patterns.why_symmetric: Limitation explains why workaround needed; workaround addresses limitation

patterns.description: Same device brand/model but different component issue
examples: iPhone battery drain paired with iPhone speaker distortion fix
Printer paper jam paired with printer WiFi connection troubleshooting
patterns.why_negative: Same device but independent hardware/software systems

patterns.example: Achieve crispy chicken skin → Use dry brine overnight → Pat dry, refrigerate uncovered 8 hours
patterns.why_asymmetric: Execution detail enables outcome; outcome doesn't help someone already executing

patterns.example: High-starch potatoes ↔ Best for fluffy mashed potatoes
patterns.why_symmetric: Property explains why method works; method leverages property

patterns.description: Same cuisine or ingredient but different dish goals
examples: Making pasta al dente paired with making pasta dough from scratch
Grilling steak paired with making beef stock
patterns.why_negative: Same ingredient domain but functionally unrelated preparations

patterns.example: Master organic chemistry reactions → Use mechanism mapping → Draw electron flow for each step daily
patterns.why_asymmetric: Implementation enables goal; goal doesn't help someone already implementing

patterns.example: Spaced repetition strengthens memory ↔ Review flashcards at increasing intervals
patterns.why_symmetric: Principle explains why technique works; technique applies principle

patterns.description: Same subject area but different skill being developed
examples: Memorizing vocabulary paired with improving pronunciation
Understanding calculus concepts paired with improving calculation speed

patterns.example: Launch product in 6 months → Use agile sprints → 2-week iterations with daily standups
patterns.why_asymmetric: Execution steps achieve objective; objective doesn't guide someone mid-execution

patterns.example: Limited budget ↔ Prioritize MVP features only
patterns.why_symmetric: Constraint necessitates strategy; strategy addresses constraint

patterns.description: Same project type but different phase or concern
examples: User research methods paired with deployment infrastructure planning

patterns.example: Compound interest grows exponentially → Retirement savings → $500 monthly at 7% becomes $1.2M in 30 years
patterns.why_asymmetric: Implementation makes principle tangible; principle doesn't add value to someone already implementing

patterns.example: Supply and demand determine price ↔ Concert ticket prices spike when popular artist announced
patterns.why_symmetric: Theory explains example; example demonstrates theory

patterns.description: Same conceptual domain but unrelated principles
examples: Marginal utility theory paired with example of comparative advantage

meta.type_name: Technical terms and their formal definitions

patterns.example: Function that 'doesn't jump' → Continuous function → For all ε>0 exists δ>0 such that |x-a|<δ implies |f(x)-f(a)|<ε
patterns.why_asymmetric: Rigor refines understanding; informal notion doesn't add precision to formal definition

patterns.example: Prime number ↔ Divisible only by 1 and itself
patterns.why_symmetric: Term requires property; property defines term

examples: Definition of median paired with definition of variance
Definition of mammal paired with definition of ecosystem
patterns.why_negative: Same domain vocabulary but independent concepts

patterns.example: Quantum superposition → Like coin spinning in air → Not heads or tails until observed
patterns.why_asymmetric: Analogy clarifies unfamiliar; familiar domain doesn't add to someone already understanding target

patterns.example: Natural selection in biology ↔ Algorithm evolution in genetic programming
patterns.why_symmetric: Each domain illuminates mechanisms in the other

examples: Atom structure paired with solar system (outdated analogy)
Brain as computer paired with actual neural network architecture details
patterns.why_negative: Superficial resemblance but analogy breaks down functionally

meta.type_name: Physical mechanisms and their observable outcomes

patterns.example: Pressure increases ↔ Boiling point rises

patterns.example: Loss aversion bias → Overweight risks vs benefits → Hold losing stocks too long

patterns.example: Turn-taking in conversation ↔ People wait for pauses to speak
patterns.why_symmetric: Norm shapes behavior; behavior reinforces norm

patterns.description: Same behavioral domain but unrelated mechanisms
